Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a large
drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned
and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, finely chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.
Thinly slice @tomato{1} into rounds; season with salt and pepper.

Reserve ½ tsp parsley (1 tsp for 4 servings) in a #small bowl{}. In a #large bowl{},
gently combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, half the garlic,
remaining parsley, salt (we used ½ tsp; 1 tsp for 4), and pepper. Form into two patties
(four patties for 4), each slightly wider than a burger bun.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook
to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

While burgers cook, in a second small bowl, combine @yogurt{2%tablespoon} with
remaining garlic. Season with salt and pepper.

Once burgers are almost done, halve and toast @brioche buns{2} until golden brown.
Spread cut sides of top buns with garlic yogurt.

Fill buns with patties, seasoned tomato, and @feta cheese{1/2%cup}.

Sprinkle potato wedges with reserved parsley.

Divide burgers and potato wedges between plates. Serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.